Having established the successful preparation of the surface-different C-Dots, we next investigated their spectrum properties. Clearly, both the C-Dots displayed a broad UV/vis absorption (Fig. 2
                        ) and exhibited strong blue luminescence under excitation at 365nm (Fig. S4). As shown in Fig. 2, the emission spectra of both C-Dots ranged from 300 to 500nm, with a dependence on the excitation wavelengths. The C-Dots obtained here displayed narrower PL profiles, resulting from their narrower size distribution. By selecting quinine sulfate as the standard, the quantum yield of C-Dots 1 and C-Dots 2 were calculated to be 19.76% and 25.80%, respectively. We also examined the effect of water content on the quantum yield of C-Dots (Table 1
                        ). Clearly, both C-Dots displayed the highest quantum yield with 40% content of ILs. It also should be noted that, when the ILs content was too low (less than 10%), the C-Dots did not form.
